1 Data Provisioning¶

In this document, I work on Phase 2: Data Provisioning. I made this into a seperate document so i dont acidentialy skip a step, because this it also includes cleaning and EDA. This is also in the proposal so there will be some overlap there (it is not exactly the same). the purpose of this document is that I use the steps of phase 2 to understand the data well and know where the data is coming from and who are involved in this project. this all this knowledge I would be able to clean the data better and so make better models and insights.

1.1 Data requirements¶

in this part of the data provisioning, I will clarify for who I am going to do this project and who are involved, the possible data sources which I can get my data from, and what data I want to have. it ends with a short overview of the needed data and some basic information about that data such as what it means, how it is measured, and the normal range the data is in.

1.1.1 Stakeholders¶

Through the several phases of this project, I will come in contact with multiple stakeholders. The following stakeholders are related to either me or the housing market:

  • The goal of this project is to help first-time house buyers. That makes them the end-users and the target audience.
  • I, Eva Bijker, will be working on this project.
  • The NVM is the biggest branch organization of real estate experts and estate agents in the Netherlands, to be able to understand the domain of the housing market at the beginning of this project an interview took place. This makes them an (indirect) stakeholder
  • Nearly every person in the Netherlands is going to buy a house at some point in their life. This is the reason why nearly everyone has an opinion about the housing market or/and the events in the housing market. So that would make all those people at least indirect stakeholders.
  • Although the goal of this project is not to make money off of it. There is a chance that if the developed algorithm is going to be very accurate, the real estate agents (also the NVM) will be very interested. This makes them also (indirect) stakeholders.

Some stakeholders are not directly related to the housing market but to other domains (where I will get data from). those stakeholders are the following:

  • CBS. the CBS is a government-run organization that collects data about the dutch society. this is an (in)direct stakeholder because I get some data from here but they are not interested in the project I'm running.
  • De Nederlandsche Bank. the DNB is a dutch central bank that was established in 1814 by the dutch king of time (Willem I). Just like the CBS, they are an (in)direct stakeholder because I got some of my data there.

1.1.2 Required data elements¶

the data elements that I am looking for for this project are: the monthly inflation numbers (in NL this is measured in CPI), the monthly average mortgage rates, and the average house prices. all of those facts are directly or indirectly part of the process of buying a house. I hope to get every data per month and otherwise per quarter. But because I want to make this project with starters in mind I also need a type of house in the date set (which is a dimension).

Inflation is the numbers that represent how much money is worth, the higher the number to lower the worth of the money. overtime money gets worth less and less so I expect the trend to be upwards. the mortgage rate is a percentage, the lower the percentage the higher the house prices are, and the more you can borrow for your mortgage. over the last few years the mortgage rate has been very low so I expect a downwards trend in the mortgage rates. Because of the low mortgage rates and high inflation numbers I expect the house price to be high and to be in an upwards trend. But all the information about how those variables interact with each other comes from my domain understanding research so it would be very interesting to visualize how this actually looks. Every one of those facts will come from separate datasets. this means that I would first have to clean those datasets before joining them. after I cleaned it I will join them based on the date (either month and year or quarter and year).

1.1.3 Candidate data sources¶

The house prices data is from the house market domain, which is the domain I will focus on because the end-user is also in that domain. the inflation (CPI) is from the economics domain and the mortgage rates are from the banking domain. But because the last 2 are directly or indirectly related to the housing market I will not do research about those specific domains.

To get reliable data sources I will start with looking at CBS. while looking there I found out that they have every data I needed except the mortgage rates from 2003 onwards, so I looked for other sources and found De Nederlandsche Bank. Which is also a reliable data source and with that the data was complete. While doing my domain understanding I also found out that the housing market-related data on CBS comes from the NVM but I can not get access to their database because for that I needed to be a member and you can only be a member if you're an estate agent. So I had to do it with the CBS data. If I would have had access to their database I would probably have more features in my final dataset/idea. the websites of the sources are:

  • https://www.cbs.nl/
  • https://www.dnb.nl/

1.1.4 Overview of the Data Requirements¶

  • Date: either a combination of year and month or year and quarter. it would be nice to have at least 25 years of data with the last year with data being 2021, this means that the first year of data should be 1997.
  • Type of house: the type of houses such as: apartments, terraced houses, corner houses, 2-under-1-roof houses, detached houses, etc. it would also be nice to have an overview of the total houses and the total single-family houses.
  • Inflation: measured in CPI. can be measured in percentage growth per period or with one year being 100 and then based on that year. this means that it can never be smaller than 0 (then money would be worth less than nothing) and it can be as high as you want, depending on which year is chosen as 100 (a more recent year means lower numbers than a year long ago)
  • Mortgage interest rates: measured in percentages. the lowest one is 0.83% for 10 years fixed and the highest was 30 years ago and was between 10% and 11%. so our range will be somewhere in between those numbers.
  • Average house prices: average based on what people actually paid for a house (not the asking price), measured in €, ranges between, in 1995 €48900 in the cheapest place(s) and in 2020 €863300 in the most expensive place(s) based on the graph of CBS. so the range per type of house will probably be similar.

1.2 Data Collection¶

in this part of the data provisioning I am going to clarify how I am going to collect my data and afterward store it if I am going to a version and naming system (so yes how), if I am going to reload the data and how I am going to extract and clean it.

1.2.1 What information to collect¶

As I explained in the data requirements I am looking for the following facts: house prices, mortgage rates, and CPI for the dimensions date (monthly or/and quarterly) and for the house prices also the dimension type of house. I don't want to spend more than 12 hours finding this data. I will start my search on CBS and Google and from there go further. If I can't seem to find the data I will try to find articles that used the data I'm looking for and then use the sources of that article.

1.2.2 Storing the data¶

After I find all the data I want to download I will download them on my laptop preferably in CSV if possible. I will only download the data once and I will so not update the data. the reason for this is that one of the datasets stops in 2021 so there I no point in updating the other 2 datasets if not all of those 3 will have the same dates. after I cleaned the data I will also put them in a new CSV file so I can deliver it.

1.2.3 Version and naming system¶

After I downloaded the data I will firstly clean it per dataset and name it logically based on what is in there or what I'm planning to do with it etc. After I cleaned every dataset I will join them together and name them in a way that it seems logical to me that that dataset is complete or what it contains. This way I will keep my data usable and it will be logical for me to select a dataset that I want to use for a specific thing such as making a specific graph etc.

1.2.4 How often retrieve/reload data¶

Like I said in the storing data part I plan on only downloading the data once without reloading because not all the data I found gets uploaded with new data.

1.2.5 Means to extract and to program extraction procedures¶

After I downloaded the data on my laptop I will load each dataset into a notebook and start understanding and cleaning the data. the reason for doing this is so I can use it for the ML logarithm and make graphs/insights from it. the process will look something like this:

  1. load the data and save it in a dataset
  2. lookup the information about the dataset (na's, number of rows and columns, and data types)
  3. drop the columns with no information in them (with this I mean if there is a column with only one thing in it I can drop it because it doesn't influence the data itself)
  4. if the date is not in a date format and date data type yet put it in one. (for monthly data I will use the first day of the month as the date)
  5. from the date create a quarter date ish thing that the program recognized as an actual quarter and year
  6. If the facts are not yet per quarter in the dataset calculate the quarterly values (probably use mean) and save them in a new column
  7. select only the columns that are interesting (while cleaning the data you will create a lot of extra columns that I am not going to need)

For one of the datasets I got a part of it from CBS and another part of DNB with one overlapping year, to know which if the data is the same I will compare the data from those 2 and act accordingly. the rules that I made for the data and will keep in mind while cleaning are :

  • the dates and quarterly periods should be in readable form for python.
  • if there is monthly data I should have both the monthly value of the facts and create quarterly values of it (of course also in readable form for python (in this case a numeric data type)).
  • If there is some dutch categorical data in the dataset and it is possible to translate it to English (only the things that will be in the final dataset(s)), I will translate it to English.

This way I keep my data consistent and usable and even if I decide that add new data I can just follow the same rules to clean them.

After I cleaned each dataset I need to join them together. I will create 2 final datasets, one with only mortgage rates and CPI and 1 with everything together. the reason for this is because the data from mortgage rates and CPI is monthly and the one with house prices is quarterly so when I join them I will lose some specific monthly data that I would still be interested to look in to. the process will look something like this:

  1. set the index to date
  2. join the mortgage rate and inflation datasets together and save it in a new data frame
  3. set the index to year and quarter
  4. join all the 3 datasets together and save them in a new data frame

I will use the join function and Concat function to put multiple data sources together. For the 2 mortgage rates datasets I will make use of the Concat function because then I can add them under each other (If I make sure that the column names are the same) and for the joining of the cleaned datasets I will use the join function and then the inner join, so I join them on index and because the indexes are the dates or periods I automatically filter out the dates that are not in all the joining datasets. this is because it will only join the indexes that are present in all the datasets I want to join.

Features

  • Instrument: the subject that the data (in that row) is about. in our case we only downloaded the 'Woninghypotheken - Totaal' which translates to house mortgages total and it gives information about the mortgage interest rates

Features:

  • YearMonth: the combination of month and year. range January 1996 to February 2022
  • CPI: Consumer price index, Index number about the price developments from the basket of consumer goods and services from the average dutch household. range 68.03 to 115.27
  • CPI afgeleid: its CPI without the changes in the product bound taxes, subsidies, and consumption-related taxes. range 72.2 to 114.37
  • Maandmutatie CPI: the average price growth per month, based on the month before. range -1.1 to 1.3
  • Maandmutatie CPI afgeleid: the average price growth per month, based on the month before. but without the changes in the product bound taxes, subsidies, and consumption-related taxes. range -1.1 to 1.4
  • Jaarmutatie CPI: the average price growth per year, based on the year before. range -0.2 to 6.4
  • Jaarmutatie CPI afgeleid: the average price growth per year, based on the year before. but without the changes in the product bound taxes, subsidies, and consumption-related taxes. range -0.3 to 7.4
  • Wegingscoëfficiënt: the amount/proportion that a dutch household spends per product group. range always 100000

this data also does not seem to have a normal distribution, but again 0 na's. this data set does however have a bit more than 26 years' worth of data and is from CBS, which is a trustworthy source.

features

  • Date: Combination of Year and quarter. range 1995 1st quarter to 2021 4th quarter.
  • TypeHouse: the type of house. the options with translation are: Totaal woningen: Total houses, Eengezinswoningen: Single-family houses, Tussenwoning: literally 'in-between houses' but the English name is terraced houses, Hoekwoning: Corner houses, 2-onder-1-kapwoning: 2-under-1-roof houses, Vrijstaande woning: Detached houses and Appartement which is the same in English
  • PriceIndex: defines the price changes of the supply of existing houses. range 38.2 to 189.1
  • AveragePrice: the average price of a certain type of house at a certain type, bases amount paid to that type of house in that period. (so not the asking price but what the new owners actually paid for it.). range 62502 to 601539

this data is normally distributed and has 27 years' worth of data and also has 0 na's and it is just like the other data from a trustworthy data source (CBS). The price index data is more similarly distributed to each other (the different types of houses) than the average price is.

1.4 Data Preperation¶

in this part of the data provisioning, I am going to clean my data.

As you can see in the graph above all the facts have no null value and have the following ranges

  • QuarterlyRate: the average mortgage rate per quarter (and year), 1.65-6.546667 this is a percentage
  • QuarterlyCPI: the average Consumers price index per quarter (and year), 68.413333-113.12
  • PriceIndex: the change in the price of existing houses (2015 is 100) per quarter, 41.1-189.1
  • MortgageRate: the average mortgage rate per month (and year), 1.65-6.57 this is a percentage
  • CPI: the consumer price index per month, 68.03-114.01
